pr_review_body:
So because of the binary files, I can't really approve this code. I pulled it down locally and ran `git diff` on the files and it also just says the file changed.

I am guessing these are auto-gen'd and totally fine to accept but I think someone else who has more context about what can and can't change should review this. I don't feel comfortable approving it.

@silverjam @notoriaga See discussion above

@wuisawesome one problem I realized might happen with the global timer is a pull request can be duplicated immediately if a Tick() happens right after. To mitigate this, can we track the timestamp of the last pull and only pull after that time has elapsed?

Then we can also call Tick() much more frequently and that doesn't affect the actual timeout of the retry.

For testing, we can pass in a fake GetTime() function for mock time.

@sallysyw Thanks for the update.

I left a few comments related to making the implementation closer to the conventions used by TorchVision. Note that there are a few tests failing and these are related, so please have a look to fix.

Finally what is the strategy for testing this and confirming that the changes are like you expected? Do you plan to load weights from other models, test their accuracy and confirm?

@EliKlein Awesome work! :tada: 

There are just some linting issues that's failing the CI, can you please fix those? here's our docs on it: https://kolibri-dev.readthedocs.io/en/develop/getting_started.html#linting-and-auto-formatting.

@rtibbles apart from linting issues, this is LGTM from my side!

@rocknes Just updated the Github page with the original PR and changed the title

> *[Reviewable](https://reviewable.io/reviews/vmware/container-service-extension/902#-:-MTC3fDDENJgtnhiHVtH:b-4cbw98)* status: :shipit: complete! all files reviewed, all discussions resolved (waiting on @ltimothy7)



<!-- Sent from Reviewable.io -->

@jameslamb 
Awesome work!
Thanks a lot for digging deep in sklearn internals and finding way not to make a parent aware of its children. I left some comments for your consideration.

@jameslamb Just to clarify: I have literally zero experience with Dask. Sorry.

However, all your thoughts sound reasonable to me, so I think I can approve this PR.
Just please take a look at some general Python comments I left.

@sryza @prha, I did a very rough pass at making a context specific for multi asset sensors that would allow users to fetch events in the sensor body more easily. Not sure it fully works yet, but I want to get some initial feedback on the user facing API to decide if this makes sense as the way to go. If we do go this direction, i'll update the rest of the code and clean it up. 

the sensors in `toys/asset_sensors.py` have been updated to use the new version so that's a good file to look at

i left a couple comments in the PR on specific places where I have questions/thoughts

LGTM
Good catch!
@Nir-Az please change this PR to development branch.
@codekansas Can you add same change to the following script (new kernels support): https://github.com/IntelRealSense/librealsense/blob/development/scripts/patch-realsense-ubuntu-lts-hwe.sh ?
This PR will be merged to both scripts.
